    "summary": "Since I was a kid I've been very much interested in weather. Already in elementary school I would drop everything and run towards a window whenever stormy weather was imminent. In Florida, where I lived with my parents between 1993 and 1994, thunderstorms were abundant and both my interest and weather knowledge grew rapidly. I started studying the weather models, making observations and forecasts at the age of 10. Fortunately, I was talented in math and physics so that I was able to study physics and meteorology at the Utrecht University. There, we arranged to do some courses and stormchasing in Oklahoma with a group of students. We witnessed the terrible Greensburg Kansas EF5 tornado in 2007. I was presented with the opportunity to do a research project in collaboration with the University of Oklahoma and the NOAA national severe storms laboratory, which raised my interest in doing research. After graduation I took the opportunity to work as a PhD on aerosol modeling and remote sensing . During my time as a PhD researcher at IMAU, Utrecht university, I learned about the importance of tiny atmospheric particles (aerosols) for the weather and climate (clouds and scattering and absorption of solar radiation). Besides weather, I also have a great interest in climate. I have participated in several (online) discussions and assisted the course \"Climate Dynamics\" at Utrecht University. Currently I am working as a meteorologist at the KNMI (Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute).\n\nIn my free time I like to go outdoors for nature photography, work on my aquarium or as a volunteer for \"aquarium vereniging Aponogeton\", play waterpolo, swimming, wave surfing and bodyboarding.",
